        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">Common Restaurant Fire Safety Violations in Austin</h2>
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-3 mb-8"><div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-3 bg-red-light rounded-lg border border-red-200"><span class="text-red-brand font-bold flex-shrink-0">!</span><span class="text-sm text-gray-700">Overdue semi-annual suppression in 6th Street and Rainey Street kitchens</span></div><div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-3 bg-red-light rounded-lg border border-red-200"><span class="text-red-brand font-bold flex-shrink-0">!</span><span class="text-sm text-gray-700">Occupant load violations in entertainment venues — Austin Fire actively enforces posted capacity limits on 6th Street</span></div><div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-3 bg-red-light rounded-lg border border-red-200"><span class="text-red-brand font-bold flex-shrink-0">!</span><span class="text-sm text-gray-700">Missing or overdue Class K extinguisher annual inspection</span></div><div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-3 bg-red-light rounded-lg border border-red-200"><span class="text-red-brand font-bold flex-shrink-0">!</span><span class="text-sm text-gray-700">Hood cleaning frequency insufficient — quarterly cleaning required for most 6th Street operations</span></div></div>
        <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Austin Fire Department inspects restaurants during evening service hours. What should we be ready for?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Austin Fire Department conducts compliance checks on 6th Street and other high-density zones during evening service hours — when occupancy is highest. Inspectors verify: posted occupant load compliance, kitchen suppression semi-annual inspection tag currency, Class K extinguisher presence and annual tag, fire alarm panel status, and egress pathway clearance. Have current inspection documentation immediately accessible — not in a back-office filing cabinet.</p></div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 mb-8"><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Does every Austin restaurant need a kitchen fire suppression system?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Yes. All commercial cooking operations in Austin producing grease-laden vapors must have an automatic wet chemical suppression system under NFPA 96 and the International Fire Code (IFC). This applies to restaurants, bars with food service, hotel kitchens, and corporate cafeterias.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How often does kitchen fire suppression need to be inspected in Austin?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">NFPA 96 requires semi-annual inspection — twice per year — for all commercial kitchen suppression systems. Inspection must be performed by a licensed contractor and documented. The Austin Fire Department enforces this requirement.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How much does kitchen suppression inspection cost in Austin?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">$165–$360 per system per system. Budget for two inspections annually.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">What is the most common kitchen fire safety violation in Austin?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Common violations in Austin include: Overdue semi-annual suppression in 6th Street and Rainey Street kitchens; Occupant load violations in entertainment venues — Austin Fire actively enforces posted capacity limits on 6th Street.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Who licenses kitchen suppression contractors in TX?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">The Texas State Fire Marshal's Office ((512) 676-6000) licenses fire protection contractors statewide. Verify your suppression contractor holds current TX credentials before scheduling service.</p></div></div>
